                <div style="position: absolute; left: -5000px;"><input type="text" name="b_c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b_c4087a59c7" tabindex="-1" value=""></div>

            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>It was not that I thought I would have wasted all that time I spent hammering obscure sports knowledge into my brain, and it wasn’t that I could not let go of the past—I just wanted to make the younger version of myself smile if he were able to peer into the future 14 years later.</p>
<p>I know it may seem like a ridiculous reason to continue committing myself to something I was not going to pursue in the future. But not everything has to be done with one eye on the future, and little by little, I started to enjoy writing again. I began taking pride in the little things that don’t necessarily pop out when sorting through my now-226 bylines, especially the work I have put in covering a struggling women’s lacrosse team the past four years and this <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2017/09/more-than-just-football" target="_blank">column</a> that received a decent amount of flack.</p>
<p>This vision of my younger self made every part of the process so much better. That’s not to say anything about writers who write to tell stories—that’s an amazing reason to report too. But for me, to be unapologetically Benjamin Aaron Feder, I needed to isolate the reason for continuing to do something that on its own was none too enjoyable for me.</p>
<p>And for that, I have to thank my seven-year-old self.</p>
<p><em>Ben Feder will graduate this May with his B.S. in statistical science. He is still pursuing opportunities in the data science field, so feel free to offer him a job.&nbsp;</em></p>

